## One Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Solitaire Ring

The 1ct pear shaped solitaire is the definitive configuration for this search — it is the size where the pear silhouette reads distinctly and where solitaire simplicity makes the most visual sense.

At 1ct, a well-proportioned pear diamond measures approximately 8mm × 5.5mm at a 1.58 L/W ratio. On a size 6 ring finger, this covers approximately half the finger width and extends from knuckle to mid-phalanx — the perfect scale for a solitaire that wants to be noticed without overwhelming the hand.

**Complete 1ct pear solitaire ring prices ({{year}}):**

| Stone | Setting | Metal | Total |
|-------|---------|-------|-------|
| Lab, D-IF, Ideal (IGI) ~$1,006 | Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire | 14k White Gold | ~$2,261 |
| Lab, G-VS2, Ideal (IGI) ~$800 | Tapered Solitaire (JA) | 14k Yellow Gold | ~$2,450 |
| Natural, G-VS2, Ideal (GIA) $3,150 | Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire | 14k White Gold | ~$4,405 |
| Natural, G-VS2, Ideal (GIA) $3,150 | Six-Prong Hidden Halo | Platinum | ~$5,185 |
| Natural, D-VS1, Ideal (GIA) $3,810 | Cathedral Solitaire (Zac Posen) | Platinum | ~$6,190 |

The **[$3,150 natural G-VS2 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28393670?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** is the best value 1ct natural pear on Blue Nile in this tier. It meets The Solitaire Covenant standard: G color reads clean against white gold, VS2 is eye-clean at this size, and Ideal cut guarantees even light return across the face. Our [Blue Nile review](/blue-nile) covers the retailer's return policy, stone inspection process, and price guarantee in full.

In a yellow gold Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire at $1,255, the total ring cost lands at $4,405 — the most cost-efficient 1ct natural pear solitaire configuration at this quality standard.

---

## Pear Solitaire Diamond Ring by Metal

Every setting in the tables above comes in all four metals. The choice changes the total ring price by $200–$800 and changes the visual result significantly.

**White gold pear solitaire:** The neutral, cool-white metal maximizes the solitaire aesthetic — the ring reads diamond-first with no warm metal competing for the eye. Requires rhodium replating every 1–3 years. Best for G-H color pear diamonds.

**Yellow gold pear solitaire:** The warm metal is enjoying a significant resurgence in the solitaire category. A pear diamond solitaire in yellow gold reads vintage and distinctive — the warm metal contrasts with the white brilliance of the stone in a way that platinum cannot replicate. Apply the Metal Multiplier Effect (explained in the [pear shaped diamond ring settings guide](/pear-shaped-diamond-ring)): buy an H-I color stone in yellow gold and save $500–$1,000 vs. the G color you would need in white gold.

**Rose gold pear solitaire:** The most romantic of the four metals for a solitaire. The pink-copper tone creates warmth that reads soft and distinctive. Works best with H-J color pear diamonds where the warm metal masks any slight color tinting. The Leaf Solitaire Plus at $1,630 in rose gold is one of the most cohesive pear solitaire configurations in the catalog — the organic leaf detailing on the prongs complements the natural teardrop shape of the pear stone.

[![Pear shaped solitaire diamond ring in rose gold — Blue Nile catalog view](/images/pear-shaped-solitaire-diamond-ring-rose-gold-2.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?styleIDs=solitaire&MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Platinum pear solitaire:** The highest-durability metal for a solitaire. Platinum prongs maintain grip over decades without deforming. The V-prong holding the pear tip is most secure in platinum for a ring worn daily for life. All white gold prices in the tables above run approximately $500–$700 less than their platinum equivalents — the premium is worth paying for an engagement ring.

