## Final Verdict: The Best Pear Shaped Solitaire Diamond Ring for Every Budget

**Under $2,500 total:** 1ct lab pear (G-VS2, IGI Ideal) + Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire in 14k yellow gold ($1,255). Total: ~$2,255. This is the most complete pear solitaire at the lowest price point — a real diamond, an eye-clean stone, and the most field-tested solitaire setting in the catalog.

**$4,000–$6,000 total:** 1ct natural pear (G-VS2, GIA Ideal, $3,150) + Tapered Solitaire by James Allen in 14k white gold ($1,650). Total: ~$4,800. The tapering shank makes the center stone look slightly larger than its actual face-up dimensions. The James Allen setting has 62 reviews — the second-most-reviewed option in the catalog.

**$6,000–$10,000 total:** 1ct natural pear (D-VS1, GIA Ideal, $3,810) + Cathedral Solitaire by Zac Zac Posen in platinum ($2,380). Total: ~$6,190. Platinum maximizes V-prong security, the cathedral elevation adds presence, and the Zac Posen design is distinctively architectural without being fashion-forward.

**$10,000–$20,000 total:** 1.5ct natural pear (G-VS1, GIA Ideal, ~$8,500) + Six-Prong Hidden Halo Solitaire in platinum ($2,035). Total: ~$10,535. At 1.5ct, six prongs provide better stone retention than four for a stone this size. The hidden halo adds profile sparkle without framing a stone that at this weight already commands the full visual field.

**$20,000+:** 2ct natural pear (E-VVS1, GIA Ideal, $22,610) + Wide Band Solitaire Plus in platinum ($2,610). Total: ~$25,220. The wide band scales proportionally with a 2ct center stone — a standard thin band would look undersized against a stone of this footprint.

---

> "A solitaire is where a pear diamond either wins or gets exposed. There is no halo to make a poorly-cut stone look alive. There is no pavé to distract from a severe bow-tie. The stone has to earn its position.
>
> This is why I tell buyers who want a pear solitaire to spend more on the stone and less on the setting than they originally planned. The Petite Hidden Halo at $1,255 is an excellent setting. An Ideal-cut G-VS2 pear diamond is a non-negotiable minimum for it.
>
> The Prong Count Decision matters too. Four prongs look cleaner. Six prongs hold the stone longer. For an engagement ring worn daily for life, I lean toward six — but I will not tell you four is wrong. Just make sure the tip has a V-prong regardless of which count you choose." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

