## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is a pear shaped solitaire diamond ring?

A pear shaped solitaire diamond ring features a pear cut (teardrop cut) diamond held by prongs alone, with no surrounding halo, no side stones, and no pavé diamonds on the shank. The solitaire setting exposes the maximum surface area of the pear diamond and allows the asymmetrical silhouette to read without visual competition. It is the purest expression of the pear shape in ring form.

### How much does a pear shaped solitaire diamond ring cost?

Setting costs range from **$1,255** (Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire in 14k gold) to **$2,850** (Chevron Solitaire Plus in platinum) on Blue Nile. Add the center stone: 1ct lab pear from ~$800–$1,006; 1ct natural pear from $3,150. Complete 1ct pear solitaire rings start at **~$2,255** with a lab stone in yellow gold, or **~$4,405** with a natural GIA Ideal stone in white gold.

### What is the best solitaire setting for a pear diamond?

The Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire Plus ($1,255, 81 reviews) is the most proven and versatile choice. For buyers who prioritize stone security for daily engagement ring wear, the Six-Prong Solitaire Plus Hidden Halo ($1,675, 20 reviews) provides an extra two prongs plus a hidden halo for maximum retention. For buyers who want a designer name and architectural elevation, the Cathedral Solitaire Plus by Zac Zac Posen ($1,800, 51 reviews) is the most-reviewed premium option.

### Should a pear solitaire have 4 prongs or 6 prongs?

4 prongs show more of the pear diamond's surface and create a cleaner, airier look. 6 prongs hold the stone with more contact points — better for engagement ring daily wear over decades. Regardless of count, the prong at the pointed tip must be a V-prong, not a round prong. The V-prong wraps the tip in a protective metal cup; a round prong creates a single-point contact that risks chipping under impact.

### What color diamond is best for a pear solitaire in white gold?

G is the minimum recommended color grade for a pear solitaire in white gold or platinum. The open setting with neutral metal background makes any body color more visible than it would be in a halo or yellow gold solitaire. H is acceptable on a careful budget. Anything below H in a white metal solitaire setting will read noticeably warm — and in a solitaire, there is nothing else in the ring to redirect the viewer's eye.

### What L/W ratio is best for a pear shaped solitaire ring?

1.55–1.65 is the optimal range for pear solitaire settings. This range provides clear, identifiable pear shape elongation without being so narrow that the stone looks thin or fragile in the open setting. Ratios above 1.70 can look overly elongated in a solitaire without a halo to frame the proportions. Ratios below 1.50 look compact and close to an oval.

### Is a pear solitaire better than a pear halo?

A solitaire is better for showing the pear silhouette cleanly and for maximum finger-elongating effect. A halo is better for increasing apparent stone size and total ring sparkle. At 1ct+ center stones, the solitaire is the recommended choice — the pear diamond is large enough to carry the ring alone. Below 0.90ct, a halo provides valuable apparent size increase that a solitaire cannot replicate.

### Can I put a pear diamond in any solitaire setting?

Not all solitaire settings are compatible with pear diamonds. The setting must accommodate the asymmetrical silhouette with one pointed end — which means the basket opening must allow the pear's irregular outline, and one prong at the pointed tip must be a V-prong specifically. All settings in the tables in this guide are compatible with pear center stones and configured with appropriate tip protection.

### What is the one carat pear shaped solitaire ring price?

A 1ct pear shaped solitaire ring total price ranges from approximately $2,261 (lab, D-IF, Petite Hidden Halo in white gold) to $6,190 (natural, D-VS1, Cathedral Solitaire in platinum). The most popular 1ct pear solitaire configuration — natural G-VS2 Ideal in a Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire in 14k white gold — lands at approximately $4,405.

### Which Blue Nile pear solitaire setting has the most reviews?

The Petite Hidden Halo Solitaire Plus has 81 reviews across all metal variants, making it the most reviewed solitaire setting for pear diamonds in Blue Nile's catalog. The Tapered Solitaire with Pavé Accent by James Allen has 62 reviews; the Cathedral Solitaire Plus by Zac Zac Posen has 51. Review counts indicate volume of real-world purchases — the Petite Hidden Halo's 81 reviews confirm it as the tested-and-proven starting point for pear solitaire buyers.

### What is the difference between a solitaire and a hidden halo solitaire for pear diamonds?

A standard solitaire has only prongs holding the center stone — nothing else. A hidden halo solitaire adds a ring of small accent diamonds beneath the center stone, set in a channel that is visible from the side and profile but not from the face-up view. From above, a hidden halo solitaire reads as a clean solitaire. From the side, there is additional sparkle. The hidden halo does not frame the pear silhouette the way a visible halo does — it adds radiance without changing the top-view aesthetic.

### Is platinum or white gold better for a pear diamond solitaire?

Platinum is better for long-term engagement ring wear. Platinum is denser than white gold, holds prongs tighter over decades, and never requires replating to maintain its white finish. White gold requires rhodium plating every 1–3 years. For a solitaire worn daily for life, the V-prong at the pear tip maintains its grip longer in platinum. The setting cost premium (approximately $500–$700) is justified for a ring meant to last a lifetime.

### How do I choose between pear solitaire settings on Blue Nile?

Start with review count — the Petite Hidden Halo (81), Tapered Solitaire JA (62), and Cathedral Zac Posen (51) have the most real buyer feedback. Then filter by style: plain vs. hidden halo vs. pavé accent. Then choose your shank style: standard, knife edge, twist, leaf, chevron, or wide band. Finally select metal based on your stone's color grade and apply the Metal Multiplier Effect — G-H for white metal, H-I for yellow or rose gold.

